g responsibility. Army and navy were a sure shield for the mother country and the subject peoples alike. Boys' brigades and Scouts stiffened the backbone of youth who flocked to join. In this illuminating study John M. Mackenzie explores the manifestations of the imperial idea, from the trappings of royalty through writers like G. A. Henty to the humble cigarette card. He shows that it was so powerful and pervasive that it outlived the passing of Empire itself and, as events such as the Falklands 'adventure' showed, the embers continue to smoulder.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBBC.  aBritish empire.  acinema.  aeducation.  aimperial exhibitions.  aimperial history.  aimperial propaganda.  ainnovative advertisers.  ajuvenile literature.  amilitarism.  amusic hall.  anew morality.  anew popular imperialism.  apatriotism.  aracialism.  aradio.  aregenerative Empire.  atheatre.  ayouth movements.1 aMackenzie, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152611954440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526119544423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526119544/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles